segments.text: This is an interview with Dennis Ingram by John Backus on November 26, 1988, at his home in Irving, Texas, concerning the Vietnam War.
In the interest of accumulating knowledge about the war, I'm going to donate this tape to the Texas A&M Oral History Collection in the University Archives.
Is this all right with you?
Yes.
Could you please give me your date and place of birth?
Wichita, Kansas, August 7, 1938.
What was your education before?
I was a new graduate before military.
How and why did you join the service?
Well, I had made a couple of research things on the 70th grade.
I made a couple of research things about underwater demolition.
I decided that's what I wanted to do, so I did it.
Can you give us a brief sketch of your military career before Vietnam?
Well, when I first joined in 1957, I was attached to a beachmaster unit in Coronado Beach, California.
That also happened to be the same base that Underwater Demolition did their training in.
It was across the bay from San Diego.
My first year, I didn't do anything but play football and basketball and wrestle and baseball for the base unit.
At the end of the first year, I put in for unity training.
And then went through 20 weeks of training.
Got it done to what it was.
I finished it out the last three years in Unit 10.
When did you go to Vietnam?
Well, actually we went to Vietnam off of what they call Westpac Detachment.
In May of 1960, we went to what they call Westpac Detachment, which was the Orient in Coronado Beach, California.
We actually went into Vietnam, it would have been about November and December of 1960.
We were the first 16 people in Vietnam.
Which unit were you with?
That would have been the beginnings of the SEAL units, the first 16 SEALs.
What's the difference between the UDTs and the SEALs?
They had UDTs back in World War II.
Well, it has grown to be what the difference is.
The SEALs will do more.
They will go through more extensive training on top of the 20 weeks.
They will go through jump schools, free fall schools, language schools, and survival schools that are even more extensive than you had in UDT.
They will also do a wider variety of operations.
We usually operate mostly in and around water.
Seals will go inland, they'll go by air, they'll go by land, they'll go by whatever is necessary.
Well, in Vietnam, what was the actual mission that y'all had?
Well, come to find out, once we got there, the whole point was the 16 of us was to teach and train these people in warfare.
We met a select group of people in this village.
And they were from all over South Vietnam.
And they were there with the purpose to be trained in the different facets of warfare.
Radios, to explosives, to hand-to-hand, to weaponry, whatever.
So y'all were actually training South Vietnamese SEALs?
No.
They were everything from Montiards to just village people.
But they were representatives of all the different factions in South Vietnam at the time.
But after we got through training with them, they would go back to their own detachments and give them this training.
Did you have a particular specialty that you were teaching?
Yes, hand-to-hand combat.
So y'all were there strictly for training?
You didn't actually carry out any combat missions of your own?
Oh, when we got there, we took them out.
Eventually, we took them out to teach us.
We were ambushed.
how to set up an operation, how to control it, how to return from it, things that you need to know to do these things, and got involved in a couple of bandages.
So y'all were over there before any of the conventional U.S. military units were over there, just the only ones over there at the time were just military advisors?
Matter of fact, it was not supposed to be known.
Matter of fact, it wasn't known somewhere between three and five years that anybody had been in there in 1960.
In 1960, they were still trying to get over the French fighting in there, been in there for ten years.
So there was still some of that
the residue of the French conflict over there, when we were there.
How did the Vietnamese look at y'all as imperialists?
I mean, were y'all looked at in the same frame of light as the French were?
No.
Of course, you know, when you're at the end of a 10-year cycle of fighting and conflict,
you look at those people considerably different than you do at the new people coming in.
Because the new people coming in, you have a tendency to believe and hope that they are going to do something to stop the problem.
We saw the same thing in Second World War.
They were all happy and delighted that anybody was coming in to stop the Nazis.
They didn't care if it was Russia or America or who it was.
But they were excited.
And then after that group had been in there for a while, especially the Russians, you saw this same angst in these people.
They would just as soon have them out of there as well.
I think the same thing is true when we went in.
You saw this attitude about the French.
And, of course, the communists, they were sick and tired of that.
So we held hope for them.
But you saw this insane attitude by the end of the American combat there.
They were fed up and sick of it, and they were taking anybody's promise.
And it cost them.
What did you think of the abilities of the Vietnamese in this fight?
When we got there, it took us better than two weeks of feeding these people, putting them through conditioning.
And I mean this was all of them that were at that particular place for us.
We had to feed them and train them again and build them up for two weeks.
We had to feed them for two weeks.
So they would have the strength to do any of the things that we were trying to show them.
They couldn't carry the materials.
They couldn't do the combat.
They couldn't do the hand-to-hand.
They couldn't do any of these things when we first got there.
They were so beat down and so undernourished, I guess.
They were just not physically able.
Now, they could walk from here to the other side of the world.
They couldn't do anything as they were in that you would be expected to do, to fight.
Where in South Vietnam were you all located at?
We went up a river.
We didn't know where we were either.
We never even heard of Vietnam at the time.
They put us, all 16 of us, on a ship and took us from Taiwan.
We steamed.
on a ship for a little better than three days.
Then they put us on a mic boat off the ship.
And we traveled for the better part of a day and a half up a river.
It was around a mountain down in the valley.
And we come to find out it was a river below Da Nang that goes inland for maybe
100 miles.
By the time we had circulated and done all we needed to do, I suppose we'd probably have been there 50, 60 miles.
It's a little river.
Well, it's not a little river.
It's just below demand.
It was supposed to be top secret, but they knew we were coming.
We didn't know we were going.
We didn't even know where we were going when they told us to get our gear.
They changed ships.
Before we stepped onto the shore of this village, they told us where we were.
And to a man, not one of us knew where we were.
They didn't know what a Vietnam was, never even heard of it.
So you received no special training for Vietnam specifically?
Well, we were chosen for our assignment based on our abilities.
And it didn't take time to see what we needed.
what became a civil unit.
Like the guys who were specifically there to run radios and communications, that's what their training had been in the unit.
Guys in different facets were chosen out of the whole West Pack attachment, out of our team, to teach these things.
Do you think it would have been better if they had maybe an isolated job to prepare y'all for Vietnam, to give y'all some area orientation, or to help y'all prepare for your classes?
Because we did what we were sent in to do, and that was to teach these people.
And by the time we left, it was only nearly two months later, they were ready.
So the shortcomings of Vietnam weren't because the people didn't know how to fight.

A lot of it was because we have conventional-thinking military men at the top who think that you're going to fight every war like you fought the First and Second World Wars, and that's the way you're going to fight this stuff.
They can't fight it that way.
And it took them forever, it seemed to me, to realize that.
Plus the fact that the guys that were sent over there long after I was there couldn't quite grasp
what they were up against.
Because some of the people that you're working with side by side, day after day, you don't realize, and you're not conditioned to realize, that some of those people are your enemy.
And you won't know it until somebody drops a hand grenade in your bed at night.
But that wears them.
And there are a lot of things that went sour over there.
not the least of which is our political problem over here.
While this is the greatest country in the world, some of our freedoms are what costs us in these kind of conflicts.

And that's what makes them so dangerous is that we have so many freedoms here that we have a tendency or the people here that are not doing the fighting have a tendency to get our people who are fighting
in big time trouble.
So you feel that the anti-war movement created a larger problem later on?
Well, I believe maybe contrary to a lot of thought.
Of course, I think a lot of people think about anti-war when they think of people like Jane Fonda.
Jane Fonda is a blister on a giant's fanny as far as I'm concerned.
She was just a minor nuisance.
However, she cost a lot of people lives.
And I think we've got politicians who ought to know better that cost a whole lot more lives than Jane Fonnell ever now.
So you think the problem with the war wasn't with the military?
I mean, the problem with the actual outcome of the war wasn't with the actual, not the anti-war movement, but the civilian leadership?
That's exactly.
There was no way you could cut it any other way.
We went in there on a flyer.
It was fairly obvious.
within a matter of a couple of three years.
We could have won if we had been in there for the right reason.
We weren't in there for the right reasons.
We were a holding action.
The problem with holding is that what you're holding starts getting sticky.
We keep pumping in bodies and bringing them out in bags.
And that does something to your fighting spirit, especially from the
a guy that gets drafted right off of college campus and said, all right, here's a gun, go fight.
And he doesn't have the slightest idea of what he's doing over there.
And out of stark terror, we start getting involved in drugs and one thing or another, graft and everything else.
And then the fighting spirit goes down the tubes.
And it was obvious.
Have you read anything about it at all or have you lived any part of it?
But the government was not going to allow you to go in there to fight a war and win it.
And we're not going to do it.
Now, for whatever reasons, and I don't profess to know all the reasons, but I know enough to know the reason we weren't going there, the reason we couldn't get it done, because they didn't want to.
You'd have to ask them, why were we there in the first place?
And if they tell you that it was to stop communism, then why did we stop it?
Why didn't we stop?
Why haven't we stopped it anywhere?
Unfortunately, the problem is the guys who dictate that we go to war are not the guys we have to fight for.
And I can tell you how to stop it here.
As you make Congress and the Senate and all the government people, you make them go first.
Or at least lead us in.
And then they'll start finding ways to stop this stuff.
I mean, do it on both sides of the conflict.
You let the leaders get out there and start showing us how to swing it.
The problem is we've got so much freedom here that we can't grasp the countries who don't have it.
And we assume that they've got to play the same way we do.
And they don't.
And we're already at a disadvantage in that kind of a war because of that.
We went in there with the idea, I assume, that we were going to intimidate these people to being good boys.
Well, they'd already demonstrated they were going to be good boys.
For 10 years, they fought the French.
Of course, the French wanted to own the country.
You're not going to intimidate them that way.
You're just not going to stop.
And we showed them.
We demonstrated that pretty well.
We've got

politicians that say they've got to go over there and take a look and they're so full of themselves that if you took them to a place that they could see the truth they wouldn't recognize it and they're going to come back and say and do exactly what they wanted to do when they went over there to take a look in the first place and that crud still exists in our military problems today
You're the one that's over there on the dirty end of the grunt stick.
You don't need some snot nose telling you what you're fighting about.
On your opinion, what do you think should have been done differently to come up with them to get a better outcome?
for somebody to determine what we're there about.
And then let the fighting man go do what he's there to do.
If you're there to establish something, get it established.
We could have done that.
We had the horsepower.
We had the memory.
We had it all.
But we were...
stopped from going into Cambodia.
You're stopped from going across this parallel.
You're stopped from going across this river.
Now, they'd come over and kick the snot out of you, but you couldn't chase them back across, and they had sanction.
And they knew it.
Now, that means you're fighting at a terrible disadvantage.
Now, we did a lot of things that nobody's supposed to know we did.
Now, it's getting pretty shameful.
that we put a name on such a thing as war, and we're going to fight it by rules, thinking that we're the gentlemen.
You don't fight a war by being gentlemen.
That isn't what war is about.
If we can't establish what we're going in for, then we ought to stay out.
And if we're going in, what do we want to accomplish?
And once we've determined those things, then let's go do it.
Because we can do it.
of the freedoms we have, everybody can say what he wants to say, much as I'm saying now.
But the problem seems to be what a politician says.
He carries clout.
It's a costly thing.
I don't know that we ever knew, that the government ever really knew
what they wanted to accomplish.
If they went in there on a lark, and then they got it on their hand and couldn't get it off, couldn't lay it down.
And everybody's looking for a way to get out with honor.
One way to get off with honor is to kick somebody's fanny and walk away.
Or say, you know, I'm someplace I shouldn't be and walk away.
Apology will get it just as fast as you
You happen to kill somebody.
No, we're going to show our honor up to the point that they demonstrate to us it's going to be costly.
And then we swallow our honor and our dead, and we still walk away.
That's political.
It ain't got anything to do with military.
That's political.
Until we stop fighting wars based on what some yo-yo in Washington, D.C. or a
or Russia or whoever decides we're going to fight it over.
Somebody's got to make a decision.
Once you tell the average military man what he's there to do, he can carry out an assignment.
But I don't know anybody in business or military that can carry out an assignment if you just tell him,
Go over there and fight.
Go over there and hang out.
Go over there and do whatever.
Somebody's got to be in charge.
And everybody, postures, saber rattles.
They weren't the ones in the trenches.
They weren't the ones in the jungles.
They weren't the ones over there with footlots.
Did you feel we should have been there to begin with?
And if so, did you feel it could have been won?
Could we have won that on the battlefield?
Well, at the time I was there, I was sent in there to train somebody.
That's all I knew about it.
I wouldn't have done
my job any differently had I known more about the country than I did.
Of course, at that time, nobody had any concept that this thing would grow into such a cesspool.
But could we have won it?
We could have certainly changed it.
We could have secured it much as we did the Korean situation.
even though America didn't exactly do a bang-up job there, we at least divided the thing between democracy and communism.
And as it is, we allowed an awful lot of instigators to die.
How should they fight it different?
Should they fight it as a counterinsurgency or bring in the tanks?
The biggest way to fight it differently is you tell everybody in the entire area
that there are no boundaries we want to cross.
You come over here and toss something, and we're coming in after you.
It's like sending a hunting dog up a tree.
You don't just tree him.
You go in after him.
So I turn to the dogs and say, you bring it out to me.
You cross our river or our boundaries or our whatever, then you expect us to come back because we're coming in.
And we were so hamstrung over that very fact.
And they knew it.
And they played our politics to the hilt.
And we never were allowed.
Based on what?
They'll give you all these bull jive stories about why we couldn't do these things.
Why we'd bring Cambodia in or we'd bring China in.
They were already in it.
Who do you think we were fighting over there?
These weren't Montyards we were out there swinging at.
So you supported it when Nixon invaded Cambodia?
Yes.
You think they should have done that sooner?
Yes.
Same with the mining of Haiphong Harbor?
B-52 strikes on Saigon.
That's right.
Or rather, Hanoi.
Hanoi, Saigon, Saigon, Saigon.
Yeah.
Coaching in the city that we gave away.
Anything you can do to establish in the enemy's mind that you're not quarantined as to what you're going to do.
They have to deal with the fact that they, first, don't know what you might do.
And number two, know that you're not restricted from doing anything.
Now, that changes the complexion of your enemy.
That's the reason Uniteen SEAL is effective.
Tell anybody we're going to have to fight a certain way.
Say we show up a certain place at a certain time.
You're just there all of a sudden.
And that's the reason that the most effective fighting groups in Vietnam were the Rangers of the Marine Corps, SEALs, UDT, the special units.
Matter of fact, I was talking to a guy this past week about, he was a young fellow you just met, his dad.
They assigned him with...
paratroopers, and they jumped into this particular place.
You can fight that war over there with a bunch of paratroopers.
That isn't that kind of war.
You were involved in that, so you know that, or you ought to know that.
Where are you going to jump?
But they jumped in, and it took them two weeks to determine the fact that they jumped into something they shouldn't have been into.
That isn't the way to fight that.
The 193rd he was with?
The 193rd?
Was that a brigade that jumped in at Operation Junction City?
I don't know.
This must have been in 1967, I think.
Would that have been... See, I don't know about their operations after I was gone.
I mean, they were involved in a lot of things.
Conventional warfare is ridiculous to do like that.
Well, Special Forces was...
doing similar to what you were doing.
They were training the Montagnards and watching the border men.
Thought they should have done more of that?
Yes.
Because I tell you, almost every place that had that kind of a situation, they were the most secure places in that country.
You can't necessarily do that to Saigon.
because it's a humongous city, but most businesses are saying that you can only go so far.
You only fight a certain one.
Who establishes that?
It shouldn't be somebody over here doing it.
So it should have been mainly left up to the special warfare units?
There's always room and there's always a necessity for numbers.
And you can't possibly have enough numbers in special units.
Not that many of us.
But you're going to accomplish a whole lot more doing it quietly
than you are coming in there.
I think the first detachment that we really became aware of was 50,000 men went in there.
Well, 50,000, I remember, you know, even 1962, I think it was, or late 61.
I mean, this was a year and a half, two years later.
And I was thinking, 50,000, everyone there, 50,000 people weighed through that entire country.
Hold on.
The first combat troops were the Marines landed in 1965.
So up until then, it was just still nothing but military advisors.
Yeah, it was just, of course, we're doing that same type of thing around the world.
They need it.
I don't deny that a bit.
I mean, these people obviously need it if they want to sit there and fight.
But the point was is they were training them to fight their war and us stay out.
But invariably, we get drawn into this stuff.
And invariably, our military, time after time, is hamstrung before we ever get in there.
And it's done not because of the military.
It's done because of the politicians.
My feeling here, and has been and probably will remain, the next fight we get into, we ought to send every politician from the state level up.
You think we ought to be?
You go.
Don't send your son.
You go.
The same thing is required of any other nation that we get into.
You send your old cannon mouths out here, and you guys duke it out.
If you can't settle it, then us young folks, you know, those that are left like you, you go fight.
to rattle all the politicians.
Are you familiar with, speaking of how the SEALs were involved, are you familiar at all with the Phoenix Project?
No.
The work that the SEALs were doing with them?
No.
Phoenix?
That was later on.
Just if you didn't hear it.
Last time they came dragging me away was about 1964 or 5.
You were already out by then?
Yeah, I got out in 61.
See, 61, I got out in August.
It was October of 61.
The Cuban Missile Crisis cracked.
I followed it back here.
What did you think about the fighting ability of the North Vietnam user that you read at comm?
Or did you not see enough of that?
Well, I know enough about them.
I guess the biggest difference is, and again, it goes back to our freedoms, the difference in their fighting people and our fighting people
We know what it is to do what we please.
They only know to do what they're told to do.
They're raised that way.
So they will take hardship much longer than we will without revolting.
Military, what makes the United States so good in military deals is their individuality.
That is the hardest thing for an Asian mind to grasp, is how we can be almost, or at least appear to be, so undisciplined that they don't know what to do with it.
So we had all these people over there with that mindset that could have made a grand difference.
Why we didn't,
You'd have to talk to people who were doing the directing.
Those people in that part of the country have lived almost on some semblance of a contract.
And they also have this religion.
They believe that it's to their advantage to die for their country.
That they will be reincarnated and live a better life.
All these things after death.
So if you were raised all your life having little, little wouldn't be that big a deal for me to go there.
That's what makes them tough.
for an American to fight.
And these people lived in caves and out in the open and just things that the average American would shudder to consider.
And the Japs did the same thing in Okinawa and all the islands.
They got into the caves and they dug trenches and they dug holes in the ground and lived in it.
They're tough people.
Probably the toughest in the whole bunch is coal rangers.
Rocks.
They terrified everybody.
Every village they ever walked into, they terrified everybody.
Tough folks, good folks.
What was your opinion of the military leadership?
Not the civilians, but the military.
I think they were more concerned about their own political ambitions than they were in leading our people.
If they'd won, they'd have told some of these political leaders to kiss off.
If some of those military people had done what their conscience told them to do, they'd have told the military leader
political leadership, you either put us in and turn us loose or you get us out.
So you think it was up to this Joint Chiefs of Staff to either convince the President not to go into Vietnam or to be prepared to resign and protest?
In good conscience, yes.
Military leadership is responsible.
to the President of the United States.
But a good leader is also responsible to and for his men.
It's rather disheartening.

You just have to believe that it had been terribly disheartening to think that you had a general that was telling you to get up and fight a windmill, as these guys were asked to do, with no weapon at all.
Tie their hands behind them.
They had to know if they had any intelligence at all.
And they said that we were loaded with intelligence.
They had to know long before we ever got out of there that we needed to be out of there.
Or we needed to be in there doing something entirely different than we were doing.
And it turns out that so many of those military leaders
became political leaders.
Too many officers were just out there trying to get their ticket punched.
I guess that's the way it would prove out.
It seems like the officers that were there for other reasons led their men and led them well.
There isn't any substitute for having an officer
that wants to get a job done and will do it at all costs, but not expose his entire command just for his benefit.
That's a man that's concerned about two things, getting a job done or not.
So I don't just sit around and talk about it.
Make up numbers.
Force their people under to literally lie to support their position.
I've seen a couple of trials over that.
Always crap running downhill.
It's always the guy down line that's really going to get it splashed on them.
Chief joins his staff, I think, just in their own, just in the terminology, tells you these people are political.
If we're going to continue to fight political wars, the politicians ought to be the ones
Going back to your actual operations that you were involved in, did you feel that the actual training that you were conducting was successful?
Yeah.
By the time we got finished, they were in control of all our people.
Each had a good grasp of the fundamentals.
each of the areas.
And they were prepared to go back and teach their own commands of people.
These things.
And then after we left, sometime later, for the next four years, I suppose, there were people who followed us in there.
Which means that they continued to do more and more of the same thing that we had started.
The problem with those folks is that they were restricted by the same politicians that restricted the Americans.
For every captain, you had a Captain Harvey.
For every lieutenant, for every sergeant, for every so on, you had a complimentary ticket there.
But they're all restricted by that same command.
And since we held the biggest stake, our politicians overrode their politicians.
Now even though you were in their country, and even though you were supposed to be there to observe and teach, their commanders were the ones who were supposed to be running the operations.
But for years, they didn't have the ability.
They didn't have wherewithal to go out and lead their people.
They didn't have the horsepower to do it.
Well, I think basically they had the knowledge and they had the training to get it done.
But they were restricted by the same thing we were.
I don't care if it was their country or not.
Our government ran it.
Do you feel that, at the Gulf of Tonkin,
Johnson maybe should have requested declaration of war and then had a draft or called the National Guard.
I'm glad he did.
He had to have declared war.
It might have changed the complexion of everything.
At least when we say, OK, it's war.
We have a tendency then to go on and fight it.
But when we tell the American people that it's a police action, and Korea was never called a war.
It was a police action.
We had the opportunity to change that thing and to end it.
Because of vacillation, we ended up getting our fanny kicked.
and you've declared war at that time and made a mindset that we were going to do something about it, I believe it would have changed the complexion.
At least it would have changed a lot of the direction, maybe.
And that's really the reason I'm saying that the politicians created the monster.
And I don't think any of them did it.
I don't think any of them had a mind to create such a problem.
I think most of them acted with good conscience.
But the majority of the politicians that even are in office today have not fought, ever fought.
They've always been politicians.
The vice president-elect, what did he do?
He's old enough to have been.
What did he do during that period of time?
Now here he is, he's going to be in charge?
At least the president-elect knows what it is to go fight.
We've got entirely too much of that in this country.
How they got to be what they are is because they're politicians.
with the American people.
We keep electing guys that talk a good fight but have never fought a fight.
And if we're going to go around and do the busy work of the world, then we better have warriors in charge.
At least they know what it is to get their nose bloodied.
And I don't want some powder puff ever again telling me who I ought to duke it out with.
I'll fight for this country, and I'll do whatever's necessary for this country.
But I won't do it because some little snot nose that had his pampers changed all the way through college tells me to go do it.
First place, his grasp of what's going on around him isn't too great.
His grasp of what's going on around me is absolutely absurd.
Yeah, but Johnson would have declared the war.
If he had declared it a war, America would have been in, good, bad, or whatever.
At least the direction would have been determined, as it was.
And as it turned out, we never had direction.
It was whoever was talking the loudest.
And the people, I believe, who were war protesters...

were protesting not necessarily about war as they were about the direction things were going in our boys and people and guys who were protesting for instance they were protesting because they were either going to have to go or some of their friends and brothers
